{
  "texts": [
    "The term AI hallucination has been criticised for its anthropomorphic nature, as it draws an analogy between human perception and the behaviour of language models (Maynez et al., 2020).",
    "Thus, alternative terms such as faithfulness and factuality have been proposed to more accurately assess the accuracy and adherence to external knowledge sources of AI-generated content (Dong et al., 2020).",
    "AI hallucinations can occur due to various reasons, including data discrepancies in large datasets, training errors during encoding and decoding, and a biased sequence (Ji et al., 2022).",
    "This poses a significant challenge for educators and students using generative chatbots.",
    "While this paper does not discuss the specifics of hallucination in natural language generation, the author acknowledges that it is important for educators and students to be aware of the particularly problematic issue of AI hallucinations."
  ]
}